==Literacy==
* ''definition:'' age 15 and over can read and write
The literacy rate of Canada, being almost 99% in 2003,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|author=Gordon, Elaine H.; Gordon, Edward E. |title=Literacy in America: historic journey and contemporary solutions |publisher=Praeger |location=New York |year=2003 |pages=255 |isbn=0-275-97864-8 }}&lt;/ref&gt; has declined, and will be under world's average literacy rates for adults in the next two decades.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/education/canada-shame.html|publisher= The National (CBC)|date= May 24, 2006|title=Canada's shame|accessdate=2010-02-03}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Education expenditures==
*5.2% of total [[GDP]] (2002)

==City populations==
* As of 2006, Canada's 13 largest cities (metro areas) have a combined population of 17,885,000
* Canada has 100 cities with 45,000 inhabitants or more for a combined population of 20,687,000
* Canada has 230 cities with 15,000 inhabitants or more

