===Merchant marine===
{{See|Canadian Merchant Navy}}
&lt;!--see the 1934 to 1935 Canada Yearbook--&gt;
Canada's merchant marine comprised a ''total'' of 173 ships ({{GRT|1000|metric|first=yes}} or over) {{GRT|2,129,243|metric}} or {{DWT|716,340|metric|first=yes}} at the end of 2007.&lt;ref name=&quot;CIA Factbook&quot;/&gt;

==Pipelines==
[[Image:TransCanada pipeline.png|thumb|300px|The TransCanada pipeline route]]{{See also|Category:Natural gas pipelines in Canada|Lakehead Pipeline|TransCanada pipeline}}
Pipelines are part of the energy [[Petroleum production in Canada|extraction]] and transportation network of Canada and are used to transport [[natural gas]], [[Natural gas processing|natural gas liquids]], [[Petroleum|crude oil]], [[synthetic crude]] and other [[Petroleum product|petroleum based products]]. Canada has {{convert|23564|km|abbr=on}} of pipeline for transportation of crude and refined oil, and {{convert|74980|km|abbr=on}} for [[liquefied petroleum gas]].&lt;ref name=&quot;CIA Factbook&quot;/&gt;

==Urban transport==
[[Image:NorthAmericanPublicTransport.png|thumb|300px|Some North American cities arranged by size along the horizontal axis and public transportation use on the vertical axis. Canada has higher public transit use than American cities of similar size and less than New York and the large Mexican cities listed.]]
[[File:McGillMetro-RushHour.JPG|thumb|200px|[[Montreal Metro]]'s McGill station during rush hour.]]
Most Canadian cities have [[public transport]]ation, if only a [[bus]] system. Six Canadian cities have [[rapid transit]] systems and three have [[commuter rail]] systems (see below). In 2006, 11% of Canadians used public transportation to get to work. This compares to 72.3% that got to work by car, 6.4% that walked and 1.3% that rode a bike.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.statcan.ca/Daily/English/080402/d080402a.htm |title= The Daily, Wednesday, April 2nd, 2008.| publisher= Statistics Canada| accessdate=2008-04-08 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080406002605/http://www.statcan.ca/Daily/English/080402/d080402a.htm |archivedate = 2008-04-06}}&lt;/ref&gt; In general, Canadian cities have rates of public transit use which are two to three times as high as comparably sized US cities; census data indicates 4.8% of Americans take public transit to work.&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web | title = Commuting Patterns and Places of Work of Canadians, 2006 Census | publisher = Statistics Canada | year = 2008 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/analysis/pow/tables/table11b.htm | accessdate = 2008-07-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;ACS2006&quot;&gt;{{cite web | title = American Community Survey 2006, Table S0802 | publisher = US Census | year = 2008 | url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DCGeoSelectServlet?ds_name=ACS_2006_EST_G00_ | accessdate = 2008-07-14
}}&lt;/ref&gt; This means that transportation planners must allow for higher passenger volumes on Canadian transit systems than American ones.

As a result of lower government funding, Canadian cities have to recover a much higher share of their costs out of operating revenues than American counterparts.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} This lack of funding may explain why there is resistance to the high capital costs of rail systems and there are only a few light rail systems in Canada.

===Rapid transit systems===
{{Main|Rapid transit in Canada}}
There are six urban rapid transit systems operating in Canada: The [[Montreal Metro]], the [[Toronto subway and RT|Toronto Subway]], the Vancouver [[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]], the Calgary [[C-Train]], the [[Edmonton Light Rail Transit]] and the [[Ottawa O-Train|O-Train]] in Ottawa.
