=== Significant sites===
While there are casinos in many places, a few places have become well-known specifically for gambling. Perhaps the place almost defined by its casino is Monte Carlo, but other places are known as gambling centers.

====Monte Carlo, Monaco ====
{{Main|Monte Carlo Casino}}
[[Monte Carlo]] has a famous casino popular with well-off visitors, which is a tourist attraction in its own right. A [[The Man Who Broke the Bank at Monte Carlo (song)|song]] and a [[The Man Who Broke the Bank at Monte Carlo|film]] named ''The Man Who Broke the Bank at Monte Carlo'' need no explanation&amp;mdash;they clearly refer to the casino. 

The casino has made Monte Carlo so well-known for games of chance that mathematical methods for solving various problems using many [[Pseudorandomness|quasi-random numbers]]&amp;mdash;numbers with the statistical  distribution of numbers generated by chance&amp;mdash;are formally known as [[Monte Carlo methods]]. Monte Carlo, was part of the plot in a few James Bond novels and films.

==== Macau, China ====
{{Main|Gambling in Macau}}
The former [[Portuguese empire|Portuguese colony]] of [[Macau]], part of China since 1999, is a popular destination for visitors who wish to gamble. This started in Portuguese times, when [[Macau]] was popular with visitors from nearby [[British empire|British]] [[Hong Kong]] where gambling was more closely regulated.

==== Casinos in the United States ====
[[File:Las Vegas Strip.png|thumb|The [[Las Vegas Strip]] is renowned for its high concentration of casino resort hotels]]
In  much of the Unites States casinos are forbidden or tightly regulated. A few places allow casinos, and they have become well-known as centers of legal gambling. Relatively small places such as Las Vegas are best-known for gambling; larger cities such as Chicago are not defined by their casinos in spite of the large turnover.

[[Las Vegas metropolitan area|Las Vegas]] has the largest concentration of casinos in the United States.  Based on revenue, [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]] ranks second, and the [[Chicago]] region third. 

Top American Casino Markets by Revenue (2009 Annual Revenues&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.americangaming.org/assets/files/State_of_the_States_2010_FINAL.pdf, American Gaming Association: State of the States 2010 Report (page 8)], accessed 11 July 2010&lt;/ref&gt;):
*1. [[LV Strip (Nevada gaming area)|Las Vegas Strip]] $5.550 billion
*2. [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]] $3.943 billion
*3. Chicago region $2.092 billion
*4. [[Connecticut]] $1.448 billion
*5. [[Detroit]] $1.36 billion
*6. St. Louis $1.050 billion
*7. [[Tunica Resorts, Mississippi]] $997.02 million
*8. [[Biloxi]], Miss. $833.50 million
*9. Shreveport, La. $779.65 million
*10. [[Boulder Strip (Nevada gaming area)|Boulder Strip]] (Las Vegas) $774.33 million
*12. [[Reno, Nevada]] $715.23 million
*15. New Orleans, La. $653.05 million
*18. [[Downtown (Nevada gaming area)|Downtown Las Vegas]] $523.82 million
*19. [[Laughlin, Nevada]] $492.51 million

The [[Nevada Gaming Control Board]] divides [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]], which is coextensive with the Las Vegas metropolitan area, into seven regions for reporting purposes.

[[Native American gambling enterprises|Indian gaming]] has been responsible for a rise in the number of casinos outside of Las Vegas and Atlantic City.

==Security==
{{main|Casino security}}
[[File:noidnoentry.jpg|right|thumb|A sign at the [[OLG Casino Thousand Islands|Thousand Islands Casino]]]]
Given the large amounts of currency handled within a casino, both patrons and staff may be tempted to cheat and steal, in collusion or independently; most casinos have security measures to prevent this. Security cameras located throughout the casino are the most basic measure.  

Modern casino security is usually divided between a physical security force, which patrols the casino floor and responds to calls for assistance and reports of suspicious or definite criminal activity, and a specialized surveillance department that operates the casino's [[closed circuit television]] system (known in the industry as [[Eye in the sky (camera)|the eye in the sky]]). These departments work closely together{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}.  Some casinos also have catwalks in the ceiling above the casino floor, which allow surveillance personnel to look directly down, through one way glass, on the activities at the tables and slot machines.

When it opened in 1989 [[The Mirage]] was the first casino to use [[cameras]] full-time on all table games.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |last=Knightly |first= Arnold M. |year=2007 |month=February |title=Blink and you'll miss him |journal=Casino City Times|pages=1 |url=http://www.casinocitytimes.com/news/article/casino-business-blink-and-youll-miss-him-164381 |accessdate= 2011-01-30 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

In addition to cameras and other technological measures, casinos also enforce security through rules of conduct and behavior; for example, players at card games are usually required to keep their hands visible at all times.

== Crime ==
One area of controversy surrounding casinos is their relationship to crime rates. Many casino opponents contend that casinos contribute to crime, and some recent research supports this.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} However, economics studies that do show a positive relationship between casinos and crime usually fail to consider the visiting population at risk when they calculate the crime rate in casino areas. Such studies thus count the crimes committed by visitors, but do not count visitors in the population measure, and this overstates the crime rates in casino areas. Part of the reason this methodology is used, despite it leading to an overstatement of crime rates is that reliable data on tourist count are often not available.&lt;ref&gt;Walker, Douglas M. &quot;Do Casinos Really Cause Crime?&quot; (Jan 2008). ''Econ Journal Watch'' [http://econjwatch.org/articles/do-casinos-really-cause-crime]&lt;/ref&gt;

