Khmer is frequently described as having [[Aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated stops]]. However, these may be analyzed as [[consonant cluster]]s, {{IPA|/ph, th, ch, kh/}}, as [[infix]]es can occur between the stop and the aspiration ''(phem, p&lt;an&gt;hem),'' or as non-distinctive phonetic detail in other consonant clusters, such as the ''khm'' in ''Khmer.''&lt;ref name=ELL&gt;{{cite book|last=Minegishi|first=M|title=Encyclopedia of Language and Linguistics|editor=Keith Brown|publisher=Elsevier|year=2006|edition=2|pages=4981–4984|chapter=Khmer}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=SOAS/&gt; {{IPA|[b]}} and {{IPA|[d]}} are occasional [[allophones]] of the implosives.

In addition, the consonants {{IPA|/f/}}, {{IPA|/ʃ/}}, {{IPA|/z/}} and {{IPA|/ɡ/}} may occasionally occur in recent [[loan word]]s in the speech of Cambodians familiar with French and other languages. These non-native sounds are not represented in the Khmer script, although combinations of letters otherwise unpronounceable are used to represent them when necessary. In the speech of those who are not bilingual, these sounds are approximated with natively occurring [[phoneme]]s:

{| class=&quot;wikitable&quot; style=&quot;text-align: center&quot;
